<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What foods should I avoid pairing with Prosecco?</h3>
<p>Avoid red meats, heavily aged cheeses, chocolate desserts, and very spicy dishes. These foods overpower Prosecco's delicate fruit flavors and crisp character. Stick to lighter preparations that complement rather than compete with the wine.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I pair Prosecco with sushi and sashimi?</h3>
<p>Yes, Brut Prosecco works excellently with raw fish. The wine's acidity and bubbles cleanse the palate between pieces while enhancing the fish's clean flavors. Avoid rolls with heavy sauces or tempura that might overpower the pairing.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Which Prosecco style works best for brunch pairings?</h3>
<p>Extra Dry Prosecco offers the most versatility for brunch. Its subtle sweetness complements fruit dishes and pastries while still working with savory items like eggs Benedict or smoked salmon. The slight sugar content balances morning flavors perfectly.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I choose between DOC and DOCG Prosecco for food pairing?</h3>
<p>DOC Prosecco works well for casual meals and simple appetizers. DOCG versions from Conegliano Valdobbiadene offer more complexity and mineral notes that enhance sophisticated dishes and special occasions. Consider your menu's complexity when choosing.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can Prosecco pair with spicy Mexican or Indian food?</h3>
<p>Extra Dry or Dry Prosecco can handle moderate spice levels. The residual sugar helps tame heat while bubbles provide cooling relief. However, extremely spicy dishes will overpower any Prosecco style - consider other wine options for very hot foods.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the best way to serve Prosecco at a dinner party?</h3>
<p>Serve Prosecco as an aperitif with light appetizers, then continue through the first course if serving seafood or light pasta. Switch to still wines for heavier main courses. Keep bottles properly chilled and open just before pouring.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Does vintage matter for Prosecco food pairings?</h3>
<p>Most Prosecco is non-vintage and designed for immediate consumption. Vintage versions offer more complexity but follow the same pairing principles. Focus on sweetness level and production method rather than vintage when selecting for food pairing.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I cook with Prosecco, and how does it affect pairings?</h3>
<p>Prosecco works well in cooking for risotto, sauces, and light braises. When you cook with Prosecco, serve the same wine with the finished dish to create flavor harmony. The cooking process concentrates the wine's fruit character while maintaining acidity.</p>
</div>
